Indiana Passes Mild Abortion Law, Media Calls It “Near Total”

Andrew Anglin
August 7, 2022

There is no such thing as a “near total” abortion law. It is either “total” or it is something else.

Indiana became the first state in the country since Roe. v. Wade was overturned to approve a near-total abortion ban Friday night.

Zoom in: Indiana Gov. Eric Holcomb signed the bill into law late Friday night after the Indiana House and Senate passed the bill earlier that day.

The ban takes effect beginning Sept. 15.

Doctors who perform an illegal abortion, or fail to report them, will also lose their licenses under the new law, the Associated Press reports.

The New York Times spews prepackaged Ukrainian talk

I continue to be amazed at the utter failure of journalists to gather facts. I think it comes down to laziness. Why think or do independent research that requires going to the front lines when you can slurp up prepackaged talk and vomit? You get paid the same and you can even get a Pulitzer if you are the most enthusiastic propagator of regime nonsense, writes Larry Johnson .

A recent New York Times piece, Russia's Deficits Create Opportunity for Ukraine, Western Officials Say , illustrates this phenomenon. Here are the salient points from the article by Julian Barnes and Eric Schmitt:

As fighting enters its sixth month, critical problems with manpower and equipment could once again slow Russian operations and give Ukraine's counteroffensive a better chance of success, US and European officials said.

The signs of Russia's challenges are many: artillery shells missing their target, interceptions of Russian soldiers complaining that they have been given old tanks, and a soaring death and wounded number in its military ranks…

US and European officials say few powers have conquered a country and destroyed an enemy army with a mostly volunteer force, as President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia is trying to do. But Mr Putin has given no indication that he wants full conscription, which would mean for his country admitting that the battle in Ukraine will be a long war, not a short operation.

Russia has deployed nearly 85% of its military to combat in Ukraine, deploying troops from the country's far east and troops around the world, a senior Defense Ministry official said recently. The Russian army, European officials said, has struggled to bring reservists and new recruits into the fray.

Estimates of the number of killed Russian soldiers range from 15,000 to more than 20,000, with thousands more wounded or missing. Even taking the conservative number, according to US and allied intelligence officials, Russia has lost more soldiers this year than the Soviet Union in nearly a decade of fighting in Afghanistan.

In its search for recruits, Russia has had to lower its standards, Western intelligence officials said. Putin has signed a law that removes the age limit for Russians to sign their first military service contract. Western officials also said they found that the Russian military is lowering health and fitness standards and issuing waivers for people with criminal records to join.

Boy, talk about the psychological principle of “projection”. The New York Times attributes exactly what is happening to Ukraine to Russia. Peculiar.

Let's start with the Barnes/Schmitt claim that Russia has "deployed 85 percent of its military to the battle in Ukraine." How are your math skills?
